The isolated CDs in ultrapure water solution were found to emit bright blue luminescence when place under the long UV light, while for comparison, the ultrapure water was not showing any emission of light (inset Fig. 4
                           ). This is the first evidence that CDs has been successfully synthesised. The argument is based on the fact that pure α-cellulose solution alone will not give fluorescence while no other reagents were used in the synthesis, except exposing the α-cellulose at high temperature. Thus, the fluorescence observed must have come from the CDs. Further testing was performed and showed that the sample was indeed emitted fluorescence with maximum emission at 435 nm when excited at 346 nm (Fig. 4
                           ). This fluorescence property matches well with other reported CDs that were isolated from different sources [15]. The FWHM of the CDs250 obtained at 250 °C was evaluated to be approximately 83 nm. The relatively narrow FWHM indicates that the CDs250 produced possess a homogenous size distribution [22]. The CDs was also recorded to show a strong UV–vis band at around 270 nm. This is suggested to be attributed to the π → π* transition of CDs250 due to the graphitic structure of the CDs that is rich with carbon with sp2 hybrid [23,24].
